        <div n="H5210801"><head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-1"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1"><hi rend="underline">Supposed to be made and sung in the Streets of </hi>Dublin<hi rend="underline">, by </hi>William Wood<hi rend="underline">, Iron-monger and Half-penny-monger</hi>, 1725.</l></lg></head><head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-2"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1"></l></lg></head><head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-3"><lg n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"></l></lg></head>
      <lg n="1" type="stanza"><l n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-1"><hi rend="display-initial">M</hi>Y dear <hi rend="underline">Irish</hi> Fokes.</l><l/><l n="2" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-2">Come leave off your Jokes,</l><l/><l n="3" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-3">And buy up my Halfpence so fine;</l><l/><l n="4" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-4">So fair and so bright,</l><l/><l n="5" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-5">They'll give you Delight;</l><l/><l n="6" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-6">Observe how they glister and shine.</l><l/><l n="7" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-7"/></lg><lg n="2" type="stanza"><l>They'll sell to my Grief&#13;</l><l/><l n="8" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-8">As cheap as Neck-beef,</l><l/><l n="9" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-9">For Counters at Cards to your Wife:</l><l/><l n="10" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-10">And every Day</l><l/><l n="11" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-11">Your Children may play</l><l/><l n="12" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-12">Span-farthing or Toss on the Knife.</l><l/><l n="13" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-13"/></lg><lg n="3" type="stanza"><l>Come hither and try;&#13;</l><l/><l n="14" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-14">I'll teach you to buy</l><l/><l n="15" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-15">A Pot of good Ale for a Farthing:</l><l/><l n="16" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-16">Come; Three-pence a Score,</l><l/><l n="17" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-17">I ask you no more,</l><l/><l n="18" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-18">And a Fig for the Drapier and <ref target="#spp-H5210801-footnote-1">1</ref><note place="foot" n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-footnote-1">The Drapier's Printer.</note><hi rend="underline">Harding</hi>.</l><l/><l n="19" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-19"/></lg><lg n="4" type="stanza"><l>When Tradesmen have Gold,&#13;</l><l/><l n="20" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-20">The Thief will be bold,</l><l/><l n="21" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-21">By Day and by Night for to rob him:</l><l/><l n="22" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-22">My Copper is such,</l><l/><l n="23" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-23">No Robber will touch,</l><l/><l n="24" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-24">And, so you may daintily bob him.</l><l/><l n="25" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-25"/></lg><lg n="5" type="stanza"><l>The little Black-guard&#13;</l><l/><l n="26" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-26">Who gets very hard</l><l/><l n="27" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-27">His Half-pence for cleaning your Shoes:</l><l/><l n="28" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-28">When his Pockets are cram'd</l><l/><l n="29" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-29">With mine, and be da────'d,</l><l/><l n="30" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-30">He may swear he has nothing to lose.</l><l/><l n="31" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-31"/></lg><lg n="6" type="stanza"><l>Here's Half-pence in Plenty,&#13;</l><l/><l n="32" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-32">For one you'll have twenty,</l><l/><l n="33" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-33">Tho' Thousands are not worth a Pudden.</l><l/><l n="34" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-34">Your Neighbours will think,</l><l/><l n="35" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-35">When your Pocket cries Chink,</l><l/><l n="36" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-36">You are grown plaguy rich on a sudden.</l><l/><l n="37" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-37"/></lg><lg n="7" type="stanza"><l>You will be my Thankers,&#13;</l><l/><l n="38" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-38">I'll make you my Bankers,</l><l/><l n="39" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-39">As good as <ref target="#spp-H5210801-footnote-1">1</ref><note place="foot" n="1" xml:id="spp-H5210801-footnote-1">Two famous Bankers.</note><hi rend="underline">Ben Burton</hi> or <hi rend="underline">Fade</hi>:</l><l/><l n="40" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-40">For nothing shall pass</l><l/><l n="41" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-41">But my pretty Brass,</l><l/><l n="42" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-42">And then you'll be all of a Trade.</l><l/><l n="43" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-43"/></lg><lg n="8" type="stanza"><l>I'm a Son of a Whore,&#13;</l><l/><l n="44" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-44">If I have a Word more</l><l/><l n="45" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-45">To say in this wretched Condition.</l><l/><l n="46" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-46">If my Coin will not pass,</l><l/><l n="47" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-47">I must die like an Ass;</l><l/><l n="48" xml:id="spp-H5210801-line-48">And so I conclude my Petition.</l><l/><l/></lg></div>
